snippet.textDisplay: Nothing, nothing, is ever free.  Dive deep enough and you’ll find the money and it’s origin.  The NHS began in 1948 after WWII.  The US did not choose to go in that direction.  Arguably, the 5X cost someone commented here is not so far off from all the taxes collected to a person living in the UK or other over taxed European countries.  The US cannot go to public medicine cold turkey without drastic consequences.  The UK has decades of experience making this successful, matter of opinion, which the US does not have.  Personally, except in major cases, I’d rather be able to pay cash , it comes from me anyway...but interestingly enough they won’t let us.   That’s for another discussion.

snippet.textDisplay: I have to disagree with the statement about our public transport being 'okay'. In fact, it made me cackle. It is mediocre at best. As has been pointed out, there is absolutely zero reliability. I would miss classes regularly because I'd have to travel from one side of the country to another (which by car would have taken me 20 minutes but due to the lack of public transport it took me an hour and a half, driving my car from home to the nearest train station, then taking 2 trains and one bus to university) and my trains would constantly be delayed, cancelled or would just straight up 'forget to stop'. From where I live there is exactly one bus per hour that drives to the city centre and anything that isn't on that route is inaccessible without a car. Hence, if I want to visit my family in the village next door it takes me 5 minutes by car, but if I were to go by public transport it would take me a solid hour to get to the city centre, which lies in the opposite direction, and another hour to get back from the centre to my actual destination. As a citizen of Luxembourg who's lived there my entire life, this is a joke. If they can afford to make it free then they can also afford reliability and structure. If they were truly concerned about decreasing our use of private vehicles, they'd start there. As for the fees, I can assure that nobody would mind to pay for the public transport, if you could actually use it comfortably and efficiently.

snippet.textDisplay: I see personally owned cars as equivalent to packets in a network. Public transport is very much like circuit switching. Packet switching optimizes for high traffic, with many different sources and destinations. Circuit switching doesn't do that job well. If the goal is to reduce traffic and/or emissions we need to find ways to better accomplish the jobs packet switching (aka a personal car) does well. Better incentives for circuit switching (aka public transit) will only marginally change the behavior of large groups of people.

snippet.textDisplay:
You almost explained that it isn't free, they're paying it for through taxes. Ignoring the fact that taxation is theft by coercion, it's unfair to people not using the services or products. As the video highlighted, if the preference is to use your own vehicle, and you still have to pay for public transportation through taxes, then that's completely ridiculous.

This is why the private sector and free market are best for innovation and production, because only the consumer pays for the things they prefer, and obviously without subsidization the cost of things like public transportation would quickly make it unaffordable for everyone using it and they would choose private alternatives. This is the main reason a government can hold a monopoly on aspects of the economy, such as railroads, because they can artificially lower the price through taxes or inflation. In other cases, they create barriers to entry to prevent competition; in the case of transportation infrastructure a government often uses eminent domain to seize property for roads, bridges, tunnels, etc. at an arbitrary price they set, where a private company could not do the same thing, which is why you see areas in the world where there's a house that a skyscraper had to be built around, because they couldn't use government force to take the house.

snippet.textDisplay:
Having been born in Luxembourg and living there for 18 years, it winds me up when people there complain about transport there being mediocre. I've lived in Bristol and London in the UK, and Pamplona in Spain, whose public transport systems I'd rank lower than Luxembourg in terms of the trouble and headache given to me over a period of time. We all seem to think our cities/countries public transport is the worst, and you're most likely wrong about that unless you live in Rome.
The point on affordable housing is absolutely correct though, house prices are rivalling that of London, which is why 40% of the workforce lives abroad. Rush hour in Luxembourg is actually dire, too.

snippet.textDisplay:
One of the things I find exceptional about trains in Japan is that when your train is late, you can pick up a little late slip as you get off the train that to the nearest 10 minutes says how much you were delayed, and workplaces accept them as a proof of the delay not being your fault.

If you try to arrive at work on time and then the train is 45 minutes late, then oh well, you just start work 45 minutes later that day. It's fantastic. If a train is late or unreliable, then it doesn't worry you nearly as much. This also means that the train network has pressure from businesses and by extension local government to operate well.

The other thing of course, is that your workplace has to pay you back for your trains to and from work every month.

snippet.textDisplay: Although this video is about Luxembourg, the lessons in it are universal. Failing to provide low-cost housing in the city causes people to live on the fringes of the city and failing to provide reliable, comfortable, low-cost public transport causes those same people living on the fringes to drive into the city and this adds to congestion which slows down the industry and commerce that powers your economy. That congestion also slows down the bus and tram networks which is a feedback loop that only causes more people to prefer to drive. Another feedback loop is parking which takes up enormous amounts of land space which makes everything further apart which makes walking and public transport less viable which makes more people prefer to drive and require parking when they get to their destination. Anything you can do to reduce single-person car usage in the city is going to benefit everyone.

That congestion also slows down the bus and tram networks which is a feedback loop that only causes more people to prefer to drive. Another feedback loop is parking which takes up enormous amounts of land space which makes everything further apart which makes walking and public transport less viable which makes more people prefer to drive and require parking when they get to their destination. Anything you can do to reduce single-person car usage in the city is going to benefit everyone.

snippet.textDisplay:
This wont work at all for a nation so small. Now if my £120 trip to London was free I would use it, but my £6 bus faire from one town to the next suddenly being free? nah. the HUGE benefit of private transport will always outweigh public transport. a 20 minute journey door to door becoming a 50 minute bus journey + 20 minutes walking at either end (so 40 minute walking). I would rather spend the money running a car than "save" £6 by using public transport.

Then make the decision that you want to do a journey that involves more than 1 bit of public transport, well either you have to pray to the devil that all your connections are on time, or you start having to go "well if i have a 20 minute wait here, then a 32 minute wait here". before you know it you spend more time stood in stations than travelling.


People joke that I walk to and from work that "no point giving you a lift becuse its probably quicker to walk" becuse they perceive themselves as being stuck in 5mph traffic for 20 minutes as being extremely slow, when it is still faster than public transport and walking. Public transport replaces walking, and that's it. it doesn't replace cars.

When the train fails, it doesn't fix itself. There's a mechanic, maybe named Jim, who has to go out there and fix it. Trains aren't late because the system is bad, it's because Jim is having problems. It's easier to dehumanize, but it's more useful to think of it like sports teams.
If you want a good network, want the system to run on time, want good budgeting, then you need good teams. The team of 2020 sounds like they're good on their budget, but they need more help keeping things in line.

Meanwhile in Asia:
Japan: Sorry the train was 10 minutes late, here's a card to prove to your boss the tardiness wasn't your fault.
China: Enjoy these high speed trains we just built... Oh wait, looks like you don't have enough social credit points. No trains for you then.

snippet.textDisplay: Honestly, public transit’s change to computerization (no-driver autopilot) and fully electric propulsion will make it transit’s such low operating costs the only logic is in making it free. Just imagine the quality of life of people who have reliable transit that doesn’t clog streets, doesn’t pollute, and costs nothing but a decimal so small you don’t even notice it on your taxes. One bus representative of every 4x4 grid of blocks (able to go anywhere necessary, that # just for rationing), interacting with each other to maintain route stability. The savings and earnings that’d bring to everyone by being able to feasibly sell their car, and the largest challenges being hygienic upkeep and onboard security. Good deal in my opinion.
